Part I - Prosper Loan Data Visualisation¶

by Tobi A¶

Introduction¶

This is an exploratory data analysis of the loan data from Prosper. Prosper runs a website where individuals can either invest in personal loans or request to borrow money.

The Prosper Loan data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

#create a function for countplot
def cplot(prosper, xvar):
    plt.figure(figsize = [10,7])
    color = sb.color_palette()[0]  
    sb.countplot(data = prosper, x = xvar, color = color)
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xvar}'''.title(), fontsize = 20)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most of the borrowers had average ratings with normal distribution.

For the loan status variable, it can be seen from the pie chart that most of the loans are currently running, followed closely by loans which have been completed. The loan status looks good as not a lot of the loans defaulted or needed to be charged off. Would investigate more as we go an as to the major factors that influence a loan's outcome

The income range as seen using a bar chart seems to be evenly distributed with most of the borroers earning between'$25,000-to $74,999'

A huge portion of the borrowers are employed, be it self employment, part time employment or full time,

Numeric values were used to represent the listing categories. The numbers were replaced with their meanings found in the documentation. This shows that a lot of borrowers took loans for Debt Consolidation.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The not employed rows for income range were replaced with 0 as it implied the same thing.

For the Credit rating, the 'CreditGrade' and 'ProsperRating (Alpha)' columns were combined as the Credit Grade system was pre 2009 and the Prosper Rating system was post 2009. This was to enable us view the ratings for all the borrowers at a glance.

The Listing Categories were replaced from numbers to their listings as seen in the data dictionary

This would imply that the ratings are not the only metrics used to determine borrower's rate

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The relationship between the loan term and rate is positive as the longer the loan term, the higher the interest rates.

We can also confirm that employment status is a contributing factor to the loan rates

The credit rate is a major contributing factor to borrower's rates. The lower the credit score, the higher the rates as the customer could possibly default.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Borrowers rate is higher for loans that have defaulted. This might be a contributing factor to the defaults.Except if the rates are raised after borrowers default.

Conclusions¶

There is a strong negative correlation among Prosper's rating, interest and loan term.To get better rates, one would need to have a good credit rating.

Homeowners are also less likely to default as their houses can act as collateral

Employment status was also a contributing factor to borrower's rate
